{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Review code quality and correctness of the changes in lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts for iteration 30.\n\nThe diff is against commit e7e3098 (iteration 28). Key changes:\n\n1. **Continuation merge preserves standalone** (line 656): `mergedLines.push(line)` before the continuation check. When a continuation is found, both the original and merged form enter the pool. The `i++` still skips the continuation line itself.\n\n   POTENTIAL BUG: After the merge emits both standalone and merged, the `i++` skips the next line (the continuation). But the standalone of the CONTINUATION LINE itself is never emitted. Is this intentional? The continuation line starts with /&+:( so it would fail hard filters anyway — but verify this assumption.\n\n2. **New prefix filter** (lines 1517-1528): Removes standalone singles when a longer pre-merged single exists. This duplicates some logic from the existing join protection (lines 1487-1510) but for \"single\" origin candidates. Check for edge cases where both filters interact.\n\n3. **Polish cooking instruction regex** (line 365): Changed from `\\b` to `(?![a-zA-ZąćęłńóśźżĄĆĘŁŃÓŚŹŻ])` as Unicode-aware boundary. Added new verbs: `ugotuj`, `ugotowa[cć]`, `upiecz`, `podawa[cć]`, `zapiekaj`, `obtocz`, `obtoczy[cć]`, `podgrzej`, `podgrzewaj`.\n   \n   CHECK: Does the negative lookahead correctly handle end-of-string? If the verb is the entire string or at end of string, the lookahead should match (no following char = not a letter). Verify this with `ugotuj` at end of string.\n\n4. **OCR normalization before instruction check** (lines 415-422): `passesHardFilters` now runs `looksLikeCookingInstruction` twice — once on raw text and once on OCR-normalized text. The normalization only handles `4→a`. Is this sufficient? What about `5→s` or other substitutions?\n\n5. **`hasErraticCasing` threshold change** (line 950): Changed `word.length < 3` to `word.length < 5`. This makes the function LESS sensitive — words of 3-4 chars no longer trigger erratic casing. Could this cause regressions for short garbled words?\n\n6. **`isLikelyGarbled` Mc/Mac exemption** (line 302): Good addition but check — are there any real recipe titles with Mc/Mac names in the test suite?\n\n7. **Multi-word garbled camelCase detection** (lines 340-348): Length bounds 3-7 seem reasonable but check — could legitimate mixed-case food terms (e.g., \"pH\", \"McRib\") be caught?\n\nRead the files and verify these points. Do NOT make code changes. Report findings with specific line numbers."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01XjLSauSC3oNEccjMzcEMnr","session_id":"cda1f0b1-248e-469a-8a6a-1e44556e08de","uuid":"7533f3d7-1b41-42f7-b41c-ae7bbd6ce3af"}
