{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01TSheS2NaoApheDMXohVHN3","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 29 → 30 Improvement Plan\n     2→\n     3→**Status:** Draft\n     4→**Date:** 2026-03-17\n     5→**Baseline:** 91.9% combined accuracy (9 failures, all generated; 0 real failures)\n     6→\n     7→---\n     8→\n     9→## Overview\n    10→\n    11→Nine generated-file failures remain, clustered into three root causes:\n    12→\n    13→1. **Incomplete mixed-case OCR repair** — the blind repair path (`applyBlindOcrRepairToken`) only substitutes `1→i/l`, `¡→i`, `€→e` in mixed-case context. It misses `0→o`, `4→a`, `5→s`, which the ALL_CAPS branch handles. This causes Pattern 7 (partial repair) and contributes to Patterns 1–4 where partially-repaired titles fail hard filters or score poorly.\n    14→\n    15→2. **Missing Polish cooking verb prefixes** — `looksLikeCookingInstruction` and `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` don't cover perfective forms like `ugotuj` (u+gotuj), `upiecz` (u+piecz), `podawać/podaw4ć` (serve). Body lines starting with these verbs pass hard filters and can outscore the actual title.\n    16→\n    17→3. **Garbled tokens evade multi-word detection** — `isLikelyGarbled` catches single-word `[a-z][A-Z]` transitions (line 302) but not multi-word candidates containing such tokens. `XxYyZz salt and pepper` passes because the garbled check only fires for `words.length === 1`.\n    18→\n    19→Pattern 6 (Mushroom Risotto — title absent from document) is a structural/scan problem where the actual recipe title doesn't appear in the text. The extractor correctly identifies the best title-like line; it's just the wrong recipe. This is **not fixable** without external context and is excluded from this plan.\n    20→\n    21→---\n    22→\n    23→## Goals\n    24→\n    25→- Fix Patterns 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 7 (8 of 9 failures)\n    26→- Maintain 100% accuracy on real files\n    27→- No regressions on currently-passing generated files\n    28→- Keep total extraction time under 10 seconds on device\n    29→\n    30→## Non-Goals\n    31→\n    32→- Fix Pattern 6 (title absent from document) — requires page-level context\n    33→- Change the embedding model or similarity strategy — MiniLM works well for the 102+ passing cases\n    34→- Restructure the candidate generation pipeline — it's architecturally sound\n    35→\n    36→---\n    37→\n    38→## Detailed Changes\n    39→\n    40→### Change A: Complete mixed-case blind OCR repair\n    41→\n    42→**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, function `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` (lines 845–857)\n    43→\n    44→**Problem:** The mixed-case branch only handles three substitutions:\n    45→```typescript\n    46→// Current mixed-case path (lines 852-856):\n    47→.replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])1/g, oneLetter)\n    48→.replace(/1(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, oneLetter)\n    49→.replace(/¡/g, \"i\")\n    50→.replace(/€/g, \"e\")\n    51→```\n    52→\n    53→Missing: `0→o`, `4→a`, `5→s` — all present in the ALL_CAPS branch (lines 879–884) but absent from mixed-case. This directly causes Pattern 7 (`S01e` → `S0ie` instead of `Sole`) and weakens repair of Patterns 1–4.\n    54→\n    55→**Fix:** Add the missing substitutions with lowercase-adjacent context guards:\n    56→```typescript\n    57→// After the existing 1→oneLetter and ¡→i replacements, add:\n    58→.replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])0/g, \"o\")\n    59→.replace(/0(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, \"o\")\n    60→.replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])4/g, \"a\")\n    61→.replace(/4(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, \"a\")\n    62→.replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])5/g, \"s\")\n    63→.replace(/5(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, \"s\")\n    64→```\n    65→\n    66→The lookaround guards (requiring adjacent lowercase letters) prevent false positives on legitimate digits in titles like \"Variation 4\" or \"Page 50\".\n    67→\n    68→**Also update `generateBlindOcrVariants`** (lines 920–938): the dual-variant logic currently only varies `1→i` vs `1→l`. With `0→o` added, `S01e` will now produce `Sole` in a single pass (both `0→o` and `1→i` fire). No dual-variant needed for `0`.\n    69→\n    70→**Impact:** Fixes Pattern 7 directly. Strengthens repair for Patterns 1–4 by ensuring the blind repair path produces cleaner candidates that score better in embeddings.\n    71→\n    72→**Risk:** Low. The lookaround guards prevent over-application. The ALL_CAPS branch already applies these substitutions unconditionally.\n    73→\n    74→---\n    75→\n    76→### Change B: Expand garbled token detection to multi-word candidates\n    77→\n    78→**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, function `isLikelyGarbled` (lines 271–337)\n    79→\n    80→**Problem:** The `[a-z][A-Z]` internal transition check (line 302) only fires for single-word candidates (`words.length === 1`). Multi-word candidates like `XxYyZz salt and pepper` pass because `XxYyZz` is never checked individually for the transition pattern.\n    81→\n    82→**Fix:** Add a multi-word garbled token check alongside the existing short-word check (lines 318–333):\n    83→\n    84→```typescript\n    85→// After the existing short-word check (line 331-333), add:\n    86→// Multi-word candidate with a garbled token: a word with internal\n    87→// lowercase→uppercase transition that isn't a known camelCase pattern\n    88→// (e.g., \"McDonald\", \"McCormick\"). Catches \"XxYyZz\", \"UuIw\" etc.\n    89→const hasGarbledCamelCase = words.some(\n    90→  (w) =>\n    91→    w.length >= 3 &&\n    92→    /[a-z][A-Z]/.test(w) &&\n    93→    !/^(Mc|Mac)[A-Z]/.test(w)  // Exempt Scottish/Irish names\n    94→);\n    95→if (hasGarbledCamelCase) {\n    96→  return true;\n    97→}\n    98→```\n    99→\n   100→**Impact:** Fixes Pattern 3 (Żurek Krakowski → `XxYyZz salt and pepper`). The garbage token `XxYyZz` triggers the `[a-z][A-Z]` check, causing the entire candidate to be rejected by hard filters. The clean title `Żurek Krakowski` at position 0 then wins.\n   101→\n   102→**Risk:** Low. Legitimate recipe titles never contain camelCase words. The `Mc`/`Mac` exemption handles the only realistic edge case (e.g., \"McCormick Spice Blend\"), though this pattern is unlikely in recipe OCR.\n   103→\n   104→---\n   105→\n   106→### Change C: Expand Polish cooking verb filter\n   107→\n   108→**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` (line 346)\n   109→\n   110→**Problem:** The regex misses common perfective-prefix verbs:\n   111→- `ugotuj` (u+gotuj = \"cook [to completion]\") — causes Pattern 4 (`Ugotuj ziemniaky. (38)` wins)\n   112→- `upiecz` (u+piecz = \"bake [to completion]\")\n   113→- `usmaż` is already covered, but `upiecz` and `ugotuj` are not\n   114→- `podawaj` is covered, but `podaw` without the full suffix isn't (OCR-corrupted `Podaw4ć` → after repair → `Podawać`)\n   115→\n   116→**Fix:** Add missing verb forms to `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS`:\n   117→\n   118→```typescript\n   119→// Add to the alternation group:\n   120→ugotuj|ugotowac|upiecz|usmaz    // perfective u- prefix forms\n   121→|podawa[cć]                      // infinitive form of \"serve\"\n   122→|zapiekaj                        // \"bake in oven\"\n   123→|obtocz|obtoczyc                 // \"coat/roll in\"\n   124→|podgrzej|podgrzewaj             // \"reheat/warm up\"\n   125→```\n   126→\n   127→Also add a catch-all for OCR-corrupted Polish verbs: lines ending with `4ć` (OCR for `ać`) that start with a known cooking-verb stem should be treated as cooking instructions. This can be done by adding an OCR-aware variant to the regex or by normalizing `4→a` before the instruction check.\n   128→\n   129→**Impact:** Fixes Patterns 2 and 4 where `Podaw4ć ...` or `Ugotuj ...` body lines outscore the title. Once these lines are filtered as cooking instructions, they never enter the candidate pool.\n   130→\n   131→**Risk:** Low. These are unambiguous cooking verbs that never start recipe titles. `Ugotuj` is always imperative (≠ title). `Podawać` is always an instruction (≠ title).\n   132→\n   133→---\n   134→\n   135→### Change D: Pre-filter OCR normalization for cooking instruction detection\n   136→\n   137→**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, function `looksLikeCookingInstruction` (line 348) and function `passesHardFilters` (line 385)\n   138→\n   139→**Problem:** `Podaw4ć letni lub chłodny.` fails the cooking instruction check because `Podaw4ć` doesn't match any verb pattern (the `4` breaks the regex). The line passes hard filters and becomes a candidate. After OCR repair it might become `Podawać letni lub chłodny.` but by then it's already in the pool.\n   140→\n   141→**Fix:** In `passesHardFilters`, apply lightweight OCR normalization (`4→a`, `1→i`, `0→o`, `5→s`) to the text **before** checking `looksLikeCookingInstruction`:\n   142→\n   143→```typescript\n   144→function passesHardFilters(text: string): boolean {\n   145→  if (text.length < 3 || text.length > 80) return false;\n   146→  if (looksLikeIngredient(text)) return false;\n   147→  if (startsWithNumber(text)) return false;\n   148→  if (looksLikeMetadata(text)) return false;\n   149→  if (isLikelyGarbled(text)) return false;\n   150→  // Apply lightweight OCR normalization before instruction check\n   151→  // so that \"Podaw4ć\" is recognized as \"Podawać\" (cooking instruction)\n   152→  const ocrNormalized = text\n   153→    .replace(/4(?=[a-zà-żA-ZÀ-Ż])/g, (_, offset) =>\n   154→      /[A-ZÀ-Ż]/.test(text[offset]) ? \"A\" : \"a\")\n   155→    .replace(/(?<=[a-zà-żA-ZÀ-Ż])4/g, (_, offset) =>\n   156→      /[A-ZÀ-Ż]/.test(text[offset - 1]) ? \"A\" : \"a\");\n   157→  if (looksLikeCookingInstruction(ocrNormalized)) return false;\n   158→  // ... rest of existing checks\n   159→```\n   160→\n   161→This is a targeted normalization (only `4→a` for now, since that's the specific failure), not the full blind repair. It runs before the instruction check so corrupted Polish verbs are correctly identified.\n   162→\n   163→**Impact:** Directly fixes Patterns 2 cases (`Podaw4ć letni lub chłodny.` and `Podaw4ć ciepło ze śmietaną lub lodami.`) by preventing them from entering the candidate pool.\n   164→\n   165→**Risk:** Low. `4` adjacent to letters is almost always an OCR artifact, not a legitimate digit. Recipe titles don't contain `4` adjacent to letters.\n   166→\n   167→**Cross-iteration note:** Iteration 24 introduced dictionary-guided OCR repair as the primary approach, noting that blind substitution is ambiguous without word context. This Change D normalization is intentionally limited to the hard-filter path (not candidate text) and only applies `4→a` for cooking instruction detection. It should use the same substitution logic as `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` (Change A) to avoid divergence between the two OCR normalization paths.\n   168→\n   169→---\n   170→\n   171→### Change E: Strengthen first-after-metadata positional bonus\n   172→\n   173→**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, first-after-preamble bonus (lines 1121–1149)\n   174→\n   175→**Problem:** Pattern 5 (Ogórkowa Zupa) — the document starts with pipe-separated metadata, then a blank line, then the ALL_CAPS title. The first-after-preamble bonus fires (all preceding lines are filtered), but the bonus may not be enough to overcome a weak embedding score for Polish ALL_CAPS text in the MiniLM model.\n   176→\n   177→**Investigation needed:** Confirm whether `OGÓRKOWA ZUPA` is actually entering the candidate pool and what its raw embedding score is. The MiniLM model is English-centric and may score Polish ALL_CAPS titles very poorly (negative rawScore), causing them to fall below even the relaxed fallback threshold.\n   178→\n   179→**Cross-iteration context:**\n   180→- Iteration 8 introduced the `-0.05` rawScore floor for positions 0–2 specifically to prevent header/ingredient leakage into the fallback path. The rationale was: \"The -0.05 lower bound prevents candidates with actively negative signal from leaking through.\"\n   181→- Iteration 26 introduced a combined positional bonus cap of `+0.15` when both the preamble bonus and candidate-relative position bonus fire, to prevent over-boosting non-title candidates.\n   182→- Iteration 27 added the direct-successor bonus (`+0.10`) sharing the same `maxPositionalBoost` cap of `+0.15`.\n   183→\n   184→These prior decisions must be respected. Lowering the rawScore floor or raising the preamble bonus to the cap value would undermine the carefully layered bonus system.\n   185→\n   186→**Fix (two-part, conservative approach):**\n   187→\n   188→**Part 1 (preferred):** Keep the `-0.05` rawScore threshold unchanged. Instead, raise the combined `maxPositionalBoost` cap from `+0.15` to `+0.18` **only** when the candidate has pipe-separated metadata on the preceding line AND the candidate is ALL_CAPS. This provides additional headroom for the existing `+0.12` preamble bonus to stack with the candidate-relative position bonus without hitting the cap, while preserving the iteration 8 floor that guards against header/ingredient leakage.\n   189→\n   190→```typescript\n   191→// When computing maxPositionalBoost:\n   192→const maxPositionalBoost =\n   193→  hasPipeSeparatedMetadataPreamble && isAllCaps ? 0.18 : 0.15;\n   194→```\n   195→\n   196→This is a narrow, targeted relaxation: pipe-separated metadata followed by ALL_CAPS is a near-certain title pattern in Polish cookbooks, so the slightly higher cap is safe.\n   197→\n   198→**Part 2 (only if Part 1 is insufficient):** If the candidate still doesn't score high enough with the raised cap, the root cause is likely that Changes A–D (OCR repair improvements) haven't run yet — better OCR repair should produce a cleaner candidate that scores better in MiniLM embeddings. Re-evaluate after implementing Changes A–D before adding further positional overrides.\n   199→\n   200→**Impact:** Fixes Pattern 5. The pipe-separated metadata line is correctly filtered, and the ALL_CAPS title immediately after gets sufficient positional boost to overcome weak Polish embedding signal.\n   201→\n   202→**Risk:** Low. The rawScore floor (`-0.05`) from iteration 8 is preserved. The cap raise is narrow (only pipe-metadata + ALL_CAPS) and small (+0.03). The layered bonus system from iterations 24/26/27 remains intact — the preamble bonus (`0.12`) and direct-successor bonus (`0.10`) can now both contribute without being clamped at `0.15`.\n   203→\n   204→---\n   205→\n   206→### Change F: Add `(N)` trailing page/step number stripping\n   207→\n   208→**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, function `passesHardFilters` (line 385) or `stripPageNumber` (line 521)\n   209→\n   210→**Problem:** `Ugotuj ziemniaky. (38)` — the `(38)` suffix is a page or step number that isn't caught by existing filters. This contributes to Pattern 4 where the instruction line passes filters and scores well.\n   211→\n   212→**Fix:** Add a stripping rule for trailing parenthesized numbers:\n   213→\n   214→```typescript\n   215→function stripTrailingPageRef(text: string): string {\n   216→  // \"Ugotuj ziemniaky. (38)\" → \"Ugotuj ziemniaky.\"\n   217→  // \"RECIPE NAME (p. 42)\" → \"RECIPE NAME\"\n   218→  return text.replace(/\\s*\\((?:p\\.?\\s*)?\\d{1,4}\\)\\s*$/, \"\").trim();\n   219→}\n   220→```\n   221→\n   222→Apply this in `buildCandidates` alongside `stripPageNumber` and `stripParentheticalGloss` (line 648). After stripping, the `isLikelyGarbled` mid-sentence-boundary check (`. ` followed by letter) won't be confused by the page ref.\n   223→\n   224→**Impact:** Minor supporting fix for Pattern 4. The main fix is Change C (cooking verb filter), but this strips noise that could affect scoring.\n   225→\n   226→**Risk:** Low. Trailing `(N)` where N is 1–4 digits is never part of a recipe title.\n   227→\n   228→---\n   229→\n   230→## Testing Strategy\n   231→\n   232→### Unit tests to add\n   233→\n   234→1. **Mixed-case OCR repair completeness:**\n   235→   - `applyBlindOcrRepairToken(\"S01e\", \"i\")` → `\"Sole\"` (0→o + 1→i)\n   236→   - `applyBlindOcrRepairToken(\"m4ki\", \"i\")` → `\"maki\"` (4→a)\n   237→   - `applyBlindOcrRepairToken(\"P5eudo\", \"i\")` → `\"Pseudo\"` (5→s)\n   238→   - `applyBlindOcrRepairToken(\"test5\", \"i\")` → `\"tests\"` (5→s at end)\n   239→\n   240→2. **Garbled multi-word detection:**\n   241→   - `isLikelyGarbled(\"XxYyZz salt and pepper\")` → `true`\n   242→   - `isLikelyGarbled(\"McDonald Spice Blend\")` → `false` (Mc exemption)\n   243→   - `isLikelyGarbled(\"Żurek Krakowski\")` → `false`\n   244→\n   245→3. **Polish cooking verb expansion:**\n   246→   - `looksLikeCookingInstruction(\"Ugotuj ziemniaki w osolonej wodzie.\")` → `true`\n   247→   - `looksLikeCookingInstruction(\"Podawać letni lub chłodny.\")` → `true`\n   248→   - `looksLikeCookingInstruction(\"Ugotuj\")` → `false` (< 4 words)\n   249→\n   250→4. **OCR-normalized instruction detection:**\n   251→   - `passesHardFilters(\"Podaw4ć letni lub chłodny.\")` → `false` (cooking instruction after OCR norm)\n   252→\n   253→### Integration tests (eval loop)\n   254→\n   255→Run the full evaluation suite against all 111 test files. Expected outcomes:\n   256→- 0 regressions on currently-passing files\n   257→- 8 newly-passing files (all except Mushroom Risotto)\n   258→- Target: ≥99% combined accuracy (≤2 failures)\n   259→\n   260→---\n   261→\n   262→## Performance Considerations\n   263→\n   264→All changes are O(1) per candidate (regex replacements, string checks). No additional embedding calls. No new async operations. Total impact on extraction time: negligible (< 1ms).\n   265→\n   266→---\n   267→\n   268→## Implementation Order\n   269→\n   270→Changes are independent and can be implemented in any order. However, the recommended order maximizes incremental testability:\n   271→\n   272→1. **Change B** (garbled multi-word) — simplest, one check addition, fixes Pattern 3\n   273→2. **Change C** (Polish verbs) — small regex expansion, fixes Pattern 2 partially\n   274→3. **Change D** (OCR-normalized instruction check) — completes Pattern 2 fix\n   275→4. **Change A** (mixed-case OCR repair) — addresses Patterns 1, 4, 7\n   276→5. **Change F** (trailing page ref) — minor cleanup\n   277→6. **Change E** (positional bonus) — Pattern 5, needs investigation if still needed after A–D\n   278→\n   279→---\n   280→\n   281→## Open Questions\n   282→\n   283→1. **Pattern 5 root cause:** Is `OGÓRKOWA ZUPA` actually entering the candidate pool? If the raw embedding score for Polish ALL_CAPS is very negative, Change E alone may not suffice. May need to log scoring details for this specific test case during implementation.\n   284→\n   285→2. **Dictionary coverage for `with/the/a`:** The food dictionary includes `\"with\"` (line 135), so `w1th` should be dictionary-repaired to `with`. If the dictionary-guided repair already fixes most artifacts for Patterns 1–2, the blind repair improvement (Change A) may be redundant for those cases. But it's still needed for Pattern 7 and words not in the dictionary.\n   286→\n   287→3. **`4→a` lookaround precision:** The current `0→O` substitution in the ALL_CAPS branch uses `(?<=[A-ZÀ-Ż])0` — requiring adjacent uppercase. For mixed-case, should we require BOTH adjacent characters to be letters, or just one? Single-sided lookaround matches more cases but has a slightly higher false-positive risk (e.g., `m4` in an ingredient line like `300g m4ki pszenne`). However, ingredient lines are already filtered by `looksLikeIngredient`, so the risk is minimal.\n   288→\n   289→---\n   290→\n   291→## Failure → Fix Mapping\n   292→\n   293→| Pattern | Failures | Root cause | Primary fix | Secondary fix |\n   294→|---------|----------|-----------|-------------|---------------|\n   295→| 1: OCR → empty | 2 | Corrupted title rejected, no fallback | A (complete OCR repair) | E (relaxed fallback) |\n   296→| 2: OCR → wrong body | 2 | Body line (`Podaw4ć...`) outscores title | C (Polish verbs) + D (OCR-norm filter) | A (better repair) |\n   297→| 3: Garbage → wrong body | 1 | `XxYyZz` evades garbled check | B (multi-word garbled) | — |\n   298→| 4: Erratic case → wrong body | 1 | `Ugotuj ziemniaky. (38)` wins | C (Polish verbs) + A (OCR repair) | F (page ref strip) |\n   299→| 5: Metadata → empty | 1 | Polish ALL_CAPS weak embedding | E (positional bonus) | A (may help indirectly) |\n   300→| 6: Title absent | 1 | Structural problem | **Not fixable** | — |\n   301→| 7: Partial OCR | 1 | `0→o` missing in mixed-case | A (complete OCR repair) | — |\n   302→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01GGSMyoXVHYzdjtsDxebzpc","session_id":"cda1f0b1-248e-469a-8a6a-1e44556e08de","uuid":"eaf9b029-0da4-4e1f-9964-e26709e5611e"}
