{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HsJtVqciNfVzyfHAHcqyA9","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have everything I need for a thorough assessment. Let me compile the findings.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: Performance & Scalability — title-extractor.ts (iteration 30, commit a2f9b6c)\n\n## Review Metrics\n- Files Reviewed: 1\n- Critical Issues: 0\n- High Priority: 1\n- Medium Priority: 2\n- Low Priority / Observations: 5\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nNo change in this iteration introduces catastrophic performance risk. The one structurally concerning item is the O(n²) post-selection filter at lines 1517-1528, but `selected` is bounded tightly enough in practice to make it safe. The continuation merge change (line 656) does increase `mergedLines` size and therefore increases candidate generation work, but the hard 25-candidate cap before embedding calls means the embedding cost is unaffected. The new regex patterns are all safe against backtracking.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority\n\n### 1. Continuation merge doubles mergedLines entries — increased pre-filter work, not embedding cost\n\n**Location**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:654-665`\n\n**Impact**: The old code skipped `i++` on the consumed continuation line, so the continuation target was never re-entered as a standalone. The new code always pushes the original line first, then optionally pushes the merged form and skips `i++` only for the consumed continuation. This means: for every continuation pair `(A, /B)`, `mergedLines` now contains `[A, A+B]` instead of `[A+B]`. For every non-continuation line, the count is identical.\n\nThe effect on the iteration at lines 681-762 is that `mergedLines.length` increases by the number of continuation pairs found. For each entry, the loop runs `passesHardFilters`, one `looksLikeMetadata` (2-line guard), two `looksLikeMetadata` calls (3-line guard), `repairOcrText`, plus the `seen` set check. This is all O(1) per line and fast (sub-millisecond CPU work). Crucially, the 25-candidate cap at line 766 gates the only expensive downstream operation (embedding calls). The increased `mergedLines` size cannot cause more than 25 candidates to reach the embedder.\n\n**Net verdict**: The additional candidates generated by standalone originals may push the pool above 25 more often, triggering the sort-and-slice at line 767. That sort is O(k log k) where k is the candidate count. With k realistically in the 20-60 range for a recipe page, this is completely negligible.\n\n**No action required, but worth monitoring** if OCR output pages are ever unusually dense with lines matching `/^[/&+:(]/`.\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Priority\n\n### 2. OCR normalization in `passesHardFilters` — two extra regex calls on every candidate\n\n**Location**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:419-422`\n\n**Impact**: Both lookbehind regexes (`/(?<=[a-zà-ż])4/g` and `/4(?=[a-zà-ż])/g`) are safe — no backtracking risk. Lookbehinds of fixed width are evaluated in O(n) per call. Because of the short-circuit guard `if (ocrNormForInstruction !== text)`, `looksLikeCookingInstruction` is only re-invoked when the string actually changed (i.e., when a digit-4 was found adjacent to a lowercase letter). This is rare in practice.\n\nThe cost path is: every candidate that reaches line 419 has already passed six prior checks. Strings that reach here are usually legitimate title candidates, so the `4`-adjacent pattern is uncommon. The two `.replace()` calls on short strings (<80 chars) are effectively free. The conditional second `looksLikeCookingInstruction` call invokes a single pre-compiled regex test, also effectively free.\n\n**Net verdict**: Well within the <1ms target per candidate. No action required. The guard makes this self-optimizing.\n\n### 3. `looksLikeMetadata` called on every 2-line and 3-line join step — increased call frequency\n\n**Location**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:733, 748-750`\n\n**Impact**: Previously, the join guards checked only `isSectionLabel`. The new guards additionally call `looksLikeMetadata` before constructing the joined string. `looksLikeMetadata` iterates over 18 compiled `METADATA_PATTERNS` regexes using `.some()`, short-circuiting on first match. Each regex is a fixed-width anchor check. For a 40-line page, this adds approximately 2 × 40 metadata checks for 2-line joins and 2 × 40 for 3-line joins (early short-circuit likely cuts the actual work to ~4 pattern tests per call on non-matching lines).\n\n**Net verdict**: Approximately 160-320 additional regex tests per page, each on a string ≤80 chars. Total added cost is sub-microsecond. No action required.\n\n---\n\n## LOW Priority / Observations\n\n### 4. `stripTrailingPageRef` regex — no backtracking risk\n\n**Location**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:563-565`\n\nPattern: `/\\s*\\((?:p\\.?\\s*)?\\d{1,4}\\)\\s*$/`\n\nThis is anchored to end-of-string (`$`) and contains only quantifiers over fixed-width character classes (`\\s*`, `\\d{1,4}`). There is no alternation over variable-length groups that could cause catastrophic backtracking. The optional `(?:p\\.?\\s*)?` group is non-nested and fixed-width. Applied once per single-line candidate on a string ≤80 chars, this is safe and fast.\n\n### 5. Garbled camelCase detection — O(words) with two lightweight tests\n\n**Location**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:340-346`\n\nThe `.some()` iterates words and runs two regexes per word: `/[a-z][A-Z]/` (two-char lookahead scan) and `/^(Mc|Mac)[A-Z]/` (fixed prefix). Both are O(m) where m is word length. Called only for multi-word candidates (`words.length >= 2`) inside `isLikelyGarbled`, which is itself only called when the candidate has already passed earlier cheaper checks in `passesHardFilters`. Negligible.\n\n### 6. Expanded `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` — 4 additional `.replace()` calls per token\n\n**Location**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:893-918`\n\nThe function now runs up to 11 `.replace()` calls (7 in the ALL_CAPS branch, 9 in the mixed-case branch). All patterns are character-level substitutions on short tokens (individual words). This function is only called from `applyBlindOcrRepairMixedCase`, which is only called from `generateBlindOcrVariants`, which is only called for lines at position ≤5. Total exposure is at most 5 lines × their word count × 11 replace operations per word. Well within budget.\n\n### 7. O(n²) pre-merged continuation prefix filter at lines 1517-1528\n\n**Location**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1517-1528`\n\nThis `selected.filter(s => selected.some(other => ...))` is O(n²) on `selected`. However:\n\n- `selected` at this point contains only candidates that passed the embedding threshold. In normal operation this is typically 1-5 candidates; it would be unusual to see more than 10-15 even on dense pages.\n- The inner `selected.some()` short-circuits on first match (first `other` that returns `true` exits).\n- The guard `if (s.origin !== 'single') return true` eliminates non-single candidates from the outer loop.\n- The string operations inside are simple: `startsWith` on short strings plus a 2-char regex test.\n\nFor `selected.length = 10` (generous upper bound), this is 100 iterations with sub-microsecond work each. **This is safe.** The only way this could become notable is if a broken scoring pass returned 50+ candidates above threshold, which would indicate a bug in the scoring logic rather than a performance problem here.\n\n**No action required given the bounded post-threshold population.**\n\n### 8. `hasPipePreamble` explicit loop vs. `.some()` — equivalent cost\n\n**Location**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1196-1205`\n\nThe refactoring from `.some()` to an explicit `for...of` loop is purely stylistic — both iterate at most `firstCandidate.position` lines (lines preceding the first candidate). The explicit loop sets two boolean flags and `continue`s, which is identical in cost to the original `.some()` with a side-effectful callback. No performance difference.\n\n---\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The 25-candidate hard cap before embedding calls is the right firewall. All the complexity in candidate generation is irrelevant to the budget constraint because the cap prevents it from reaching the expensive operation.\n- All new regexes use anchors (`^`, `$`) and fixed-width quantifiers. None are susceptible to ReDoS.\n- The short-circuit guard on the OCR normalization path (`if (ocrNormForInstruction !== text)`) avoids unnecessary work on the common case.\n- The O(n²) filter is applied only to already-filtered `selected`, not to the full candidate pool. The structural placement is correct."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: ac11f434976a41fcb (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 28679\ntool_uses: 17\nduration_ms: 106425</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"cda1f0b1-248e-469a-8a6a-1e44556e08de","uuid":"4df53e43-30aa-4089-8b0a-8fb6ec1e251f","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Review performance and scalability of the changes in lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts (iteration 30, commit a2f9b6c).\n\nCONTEXT: This code runs on a mobile device (React Native / Expo). Total title extraction must complete under 10 seconds. The improvement plan states all changes should be O(1) per candidate with negligible impact (<1ms).\n\nKey changes to review for performance:\n\n1. **Continuation merge now emits standalone + merged** (line 656): `mergedLines.push(line)` always pushes the original. This increases the mergedLines array size, which affects downstream iteration for 2-line and 3-line joins.\n\n2. **New `stripTrailingPageRef` function** (line 563): Applied to every single-line candidate via regex. Check if the regex could be expensive.\n\n3. **OCR normalization in `passesHardFilters`** (lines 415-422): Two regex replacements + re-running `looksLikeCookingInstruction` on every candidate that goes through hard filters.\n\n4. **New garbled camelCase detection** (lines 340-348): `.some()` over all words with regex test, inside `isLikelyGarbled` which is called from `passesHardFilters`.\n\n5. **Expanded `applyBlindOcrRepairToken`** (lines 893-918): More regex replacements per token (added 4→A, 5→S, ¡→I, €→E, Í/Ì→I patterns).\n\n6. **New pre-merged continuation prefix filter** (lines 1517-1528): O(n²) nested loop over `selected` array.\n\n7. **Metadata check in 2-line and 3-line joins** (lines 733, 748-750): Extra `looksLikeMetadata` calls per iteration.\n\n8. **`hasPipePreamble` tracking** (lines 1183, 1196-1205): Changed from `.some()` to explicit loop — check if this is equivalent or has different perf characteristics.\n\nPlease assess:\n- Are any of these changes potentially expensive on a mobile device?\n- Could the increased mergedLines array cause a meaningful increase in candidates, leading to more embedding calls (which are the expensive operation)?\n- Is the O(n²) prefix filter at lines 1517-1528 safe given typical `selected` array sizes?\n- Any regex patterns that could cause catastrophic backtracking?\n\nDo NOT make code changes. Only report findings.","agentId":"ac11f434976a41fcb","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have everything I need for a thorough assessment. Let me compile the findings.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: Performance & Scalability — title-extractor.ts (iteration 30, commit a2f9b6c)\n\n## Review Metrics\n- Files Reviewed: 1\n- Critical Issues: 0\n- High Priority: 1\n- Medium Priority: 2\n- Low Priority / Observations: 5\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nNo change in this iteration introduces catastrophic performance risk. The one structurally concerning item is the O(n²) post-selection filter at lines 1517-1528, but `selected` is bounded tightly enough in practice to make it safe. The continuation merge change (line 656) does increase `mergedLines` size and therefore increases candidate generation work, but the hard 25-candidate cap before embedding calls means the embedding cost is unaffected. The new regex patterns are all safe against backtracking.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority\n\n### 1. Continuation merge doubles mergedLines entries — increased pre-filter work, not embedding cost\n\n**Location**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:654-665`\n\n**Impact**: The old code skipped `i++` on the consumed continuation line, so the continuation target was never re-entered as a standalone. The new code always pushes the original line first, then optionally pushes the merged form and skips `i++` only for the consumed continuation. This means: for every continuation pair `(A, /B)`, `mergedLines` now contains `[A, A+B]` instead of `[A+B]`. For every non-continuation line, the count is identical.\n\nThe effect on the iteration at lines 681-762 is that `mergedLines.length` increases by the number of continuation pairs found. For each entry, the loop runs `passesHardFilters`, one `looksLikeMetadata` (2-line guard), two `looksLikeMetadata` calls (3-line guard), `repairOcrText`, plus the `seen` set check. This is all O(1) per line and fast (sub-millisecond CPU work). Crucially, the 25-candidate cap at line 766 gates the only expensive downstream operation (embedding calls). The increased `mergedLines` size cannot cause more than 25 candidates to reach the embedder.\n\n**Net verdict**: The additional candidates generated by standalone originals may push the pool above 25 more often, triggering the sort-and-slice at line 767. That sort is O(k log k) where k is the candidate count. With k realistically in the 20-60 range for a recipe page, this is completely negligible.\n\n**No action required, but worth monitoring** if OCR output pages are ever unusually dense with lines matching `/^[/&+:(]/`.\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Priority\n\n### 2. OCR normalization in `passesHardFilters` — two extra regex calls on every candidate\n\n**Location**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:419-422`\n\n**Impact**: Both lookbehind regexes (`/(?<=[a-zà-ż])4/g` and `/4(?=[a-zà-ż])/g`) are safe — no backtracking risk. Lookbehinds of fixed width are evaluated in O(n) per call. Because of the short-circuit guard `if (ocrNormForInstruction !== text)`, `looksLikeCookingInstruction` is only re-invoked when the string actually changed (i.e., when a digit-4 was found adjacent to a lowercase letter). This is rare in practice.\n\nThe cost path is: every candidate that reaches line 419 has already passed six prior checks. Strings that reach here are usually legitimate title candidates, so the `4`-adjacent pattern is uncommon. The two `.replace()` calls on short strings (<80 chars) are effectively free. The conditional second `looksLikeCookingInstruction` call invokes a single pre-compiled regex test, also effectively free.\n\n**Net verdict**: Well within the <1ms target per candidate. No action required. The guard makes this self-optimizing.\n\n### 3. `looksLikeMetadata` called on every 2-line and 3-line join step — increased call frequency\n\n**Location**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:733, 748-750`\n\n**Impact**: Previously, the join guards checked only `isSectionLabel`. The new guards additionally call `looksLikeMetadata` before constructing the joined string. `looksLikeMetadata` iterates over 18 compiled `METADATA_PATTERNS` regexes using `.some()`, short-circuiting on first match. Each regex is a fixed-width anchor check. For a 40-line page, this adds approximately 2 × 40 metadata checks for 2-line joins and 2 × 40 for 3-line joins (early short-circuit likely cuts the actual work to ~4 pattern tests per call on non-matching lines).\n\n**Net verdict**: Approximately 160-320 additional regex tests per page, each on a string ≤80 chars. Total added cost is sub-microsecond. No action required.\n\n---\n\n## LOW Priority / Observations\n\n### 4. `stripTrailingPageRef` regex — no backtracking risk\n\n**Location**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:563-565`\n\nPattern: `/\\s*\\((?:p\\.?\\s*)?\\d{1,4}\\)\\s*$/`\n\nThis is anchored to end-of-string (`$`) and contains only quantifiers over fixed-width character classes (`\\s*`, `\\d{1,4}`). There is no alternation over variable-length groups that could cause catastrophic backtracking. The optional `(?:p\\.?\\s*)?` group is non-nested and fixed-width. Applied once per single-line candidate on a string ≤80 chars, this is safe and fast.\n\n### 5. Garbled camelCase detection — O(words) with two lightweight tests\n\n**Location**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:340-346`\n\nThe `.some()` iterates words and runs two regexes per word: `/[a-z][A-Z]/` (two-char lookahead scan) and `/^(Mc|Mac)[A-Z]/` (fixed prefix). Both are O(m) where m is word length. Called only for multi-word candidates (`words.length >= 2`) inside `isLikelyGarbled`, which is itself only called when the candidate has already passed earlier cheaper checks in `passesHardFilters`. Negligible.\n\n### 6. Expanded `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` — 4 additional `.replace()` calls per token\n\n**Location**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:893-918`\n\nThe function now runs up to 11 `.replace()` calls (7 in the ALL_CAPS branch, 9 in the mixed-case branch). All patterns are character-level substitutions on short tokens (individual words). This function is only called from `applyBlindOcrRepairMixedCase`, which is only called from `generateBlindOcrVariants`, which is only called for lines at position ≤5. Total exposure is at most 5 lines × their word count × 11 replace operations per word. Well within budget.\n\n### 7. O(n²) pre-merged continuation prefix filter at lines 1517-1528\n\n**Location**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1517-1528`\n\nThis `selected.filter(s => selected.some(other => ...))` is O(n²) on `selected`. However:\n\n- `selected` at this point contains only candidates that passed the embedding threshold. In normal operation this is typically 1-5 candidates; it would be unusual to see more than 10-15 even on dense pages.\n- The inner `selected.some()` short-circuits on first match (first `other` that returns `true` exits).\n- The guard `if (s.origin !== 'single') return true` eliminates non-single candidates from the outer loop.\n- The string operations inside are simple: `startsWith` on short strings plus a 2-char regex test.\n\nFor `selected.length = 10` (generous upper bound), this is 100 iterations with sub-microsecond work each. **This is safe.** The only way this could become notable is if a broken scoring pass returned 50+ candidates above threshold, which would indicate a bug in the scoring logic rather than a performance problem here.\n\n**No action required given the bounded post-threshold population.**\n\n### 8. `hasPipePreamble` explicit loop vs. `.some()` — equivalent cost\n\n**Location**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1196-1205`\n\nThe refactoring from `.some()` to an explicit `for...of` loop is purely stylistic — both iterate at most `firstCandidate.position` lines (lines preceding the first candidate). The explicit loop sets two boolean flags and `continue`s, which is identical in cost to the original `.some()` with a side-effectful callback. No performance difference.\n\n---\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The 25-candidate hard cap before embedding calls is the right firewall. All the complexity in candidate generation is irrelevant to the budget constraint because the cap prevents it from reaching the expensive operation.\n- All new regexes use anchors (`^`, `$`) and fixed-width quantifiers. None are susceptible to ReDoS.\n- The short-circuit guard on the OCR normalization path (`if (ocrNormForInstruction !== text)`) avoids unnecessary work on the common case.\n- The O(n²) filter is applied only to already-filtered `selected`, not to the full candidate pool. The structural placement is correct."}],"totalDurationMs":106425,"totalTokens":28679,"totalToolUseCount":17,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1365,"cache_read_input_tokens":24889,"output_tokens":2424,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1365},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
