{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01GGSMyoXVHYzdjtsDxebzpc","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have a full picture. Let me compile the detailed comparison.\n\n---\n\n## Code Review: Iteration 30 Implementation vs Improvement Plan\n\n### Review Metrics\n- Files reviewed: 2 (title-extractor.ts, food-dictionary.ts)\n- Planned changes: 4\n- Planned changes implemented correctly: 4 of 4\n- Unplanned changes found: 8\n- Plan prediction accuracy: matches\n\n---\n\n## A. Plan Adherence — All 4 Planned Changes\n\n**Change 1: Preserve standalone candidate when continuation-merging**\n\nImplemented correctly. The code at lines 654–663 matches the plan's specification exactly:\n\n```typescript\nmergedLines.push(line);  // always keep the original standalone\nif (i + 1 < capsCoalesced.length) {\n  const nextText = capsCoalesced[i + 1].text;\n  if (/^[/&+:(]/.test(nextText)) {\n    mergedLines.push({ text: `${line.text} ${nextText}`, index: line.index });\n    i++;\n    continue;\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThe plan's exact code appears in the file, including the comment `// always keep the original standalone`. One nuance: the plan said the `seen` set downstream handles deduplication; the code confirms this is still the mechanism.\n\n**Change 2: Add \"sole\" to food dictionary**\n\nImplemented correctly. Line 10 of `food-dictionary.ts`:\n\n```\n\"salmon\", \"cod\", \"halibut\", \"tuna\", \"trout\", \"sardine\", \"anchovy\", \"sole\",\n```\n\nThe plan specified adding `\"sole\"` and explicitly warned not to add `\"soie\"`. Both instructions followed.\n\n**Change 3: Lower word-count threshold for Polish cooking instruction detection**\n\nImplemented correctly. The `looksLikeCookingInstruction` function (lines 367–377) matches the plan's pseudocode:\n\n```typescript\nif (POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS.test(text.trim())) {\n  return words.length >= 2;  // Polish: 2+ words is enough\n}\nif (words.length < 4) return false;  // English: keep existing 4-word threshold\nif (COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS.test(text.trim())) return true;\nreturn false;\n```\n\nThe comments are verbatim from the plan. Function structure matches.\n\n**Change 4: Raise positional cap to 0.22 for pipe+ALL_CAPS**\n\nImplemented correctly. Lines 1249–1250:\n\n```typescript\nconst maxPositionalBoost =\n  hasPipePreamble && isAllCaps(firstCandidate.text) ? 0.22 : 0.15;\n```\n\nThe plan specified `0.22` (Option A preferred), used `hasPipePreamble` as the variable name, and the fallback remains `0.15`. Matches exactly.\n\n**Verdict on plan adherence: 4/4, no deviations.**\n\n---\n\n## B. Unplanned Changes — Risk Assessment\n\n### 1. `stripTrailingPageRef` function\n\nThis function was actually specified in the **iteration 29 plan** as Change F, not the iteration 30 plan. The iter 30 plan simply doesn't mention it because it was already documented in iter 29. The function strips trailing `(N)` or `(p. N)` patterns, e.g. `\"Ugotuj ziemniaky. (38)\"` → `\"Ugotuj ziemniaky.\"`. It is applied in `buildCandidates` at line 688 alongside `stripParentheticalGloss` and `stripPageNumber`.\n\nRisk: **Low.** The regex `/\\s*\\((?:p\\.?\\s*)?\\d{1,4}\\)\\s*$/` is tightly scoped to trailing digit-only or `p. N` parentheticals. It cannot strip content-bearing parentheticals like `(variation D)` or `(serves 4)` unless they contain only 1–4 digits with an optional `p.`. The iter 29 plan explicitly validated this function. No test coverage added for it in this iteration.\n\n### 2. OCR normalization in `passesHardFilters` (4→a before cooking instruction check)\n\nAlso specified in iteration 29 plan as Change D. The implementation uses a restricted version — only `4→a` with letter-adjacent context guards:\n\n```typescript\nconst ocrNormForInstruction = text\n  .replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])4/g, \"a\")\n  .replace(/4(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, \"a\");\nif (ocrNormForInstruction !== text && looksLikeCookingInstruction(ocrNormForInstruction)) return false;\n```\n\nThe iter 29 plan suggested also handling `1→i`, `0→o`, `5→s`. The implementation deliberately restricts to only `4→a` with a comment explaining this is the specific artifact causing failures. This is more conservative than the plan suggested, which reduces regression risk.\n\nRisk: **Low.** The `!== text` guard ensures the branch only fires when the substitution actually changed something, preventing any false positive on clean text.\n\n### 3. Multi-word garbled camelCase detection in `isLikelyGarbled`\n\nAlso specified in iteration 29 plan as Change B. The implementation at lines 340–348 adds:\n\n```typescript\nconst hasGarbledCamelCase = words.some(\n  (w) =>\n    w.length >= 3 &&\n    w.length <= 7 &&\n    /[a-z][A-Z]/.test(w) &&\n    !/^(Mc|Mac)[A-Z]/.test(w)\n);\n```\n\nThe iter 29 plan's proposed code lacked the `w.length <= 7` upper bound. The implementation adds it with a comment: \"True garbled tokens like `XxYyZz` or `UuIw` are ≤7 chars.\" This is a deliberate narrowing versus the plan — it prevents false positives from OCR-dropped-space artifacts like `\"withGarlic\"` (10 chars) which would otherwise trigger the check and wrongly reject valid candidates.\n\nRisk: **Low.** The upper bound is a safety addition that only prevents false rejections. Worth noting the bound of 7 is chosen somewhat arbitrarily — a merged word like `\"withSalt\"` (8 chars) would still pass. The reasoning is sound but the specific value could use a unit test.\n\n### 4. `hasErraticCasing` threshold: minimum word length is 5 (not 3)\n\nThe current implementation requires `word.length < 5` to skip:\n\n```typescript\nif (word.length < 5) return false;\n```\n\nThe iter 29 plan doesn't reference this threshold at all; this was introduced in iter 30 itself. Based on the iter 30 commit being the baseline for this plan, the question is whether iter 30's `hasErraticCasing` used length `< 3` previously. The current value is `< 5` — words shorter than 5 characters are not checked for erratic casing. This is more conservative (fewer false detections) than if the threshold were `< 3`.\n\nRisk: **Unclear without prior state.** The comment says \"3→5\" in the task description. If the previous threshold was 3, raising it to 5 means words of 3–4 characters (`\"KoP\"`, `\"aBcD\"`) are now exempt from erratic casing detection. For single-word candidates of length 3–4, this seems safe because they're already filtered by other checks (the `unicodeLetters.length <= 3` garbled check). For multi-word candidates, a 4-character garbled word would no longer be caught by `hasErraticCasing`. This is a small regression risk but likely negligible in practice since 4-character erratic-casing artifacts are rare.\n\n### 5. Expanded `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` (4→A, 5→S, ¡→I, €→E, Í/Ì→I)\n\nSpecified in iteration 29 plan as Change A. The ALL_CAPS branch of `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` now includes:\n\n```typescript\n.replace(/4(?=[A-ZÀ-Ż])/g, \"A\")\n.replace(/(?<=[A-ZÀ-Ż])4/g, \"A\")\n.replace(/5(?=[A-ZÀ-Ż])/g, \"S\")\n.replace(/(?<=[A-ZÀ-Ż])5/g, \"S\")\n.replace(/¡/g, \"I\")\n.replace(/€/g, \"E\")\n.replace(/[ÍÌ]/g, \"I\");\n```\n\nThis was the core of iter 29 Change A. The iter 30 plan did not re-list this because it was already implemented in iteration 30 (iter 30 is the baseline of the iter 30 plan). Confirmed: the iter 30 plan baseline states \"Iteration 30 implemented all 6 changes from the iter 29 plan.\"\n\nRisk: **N/A — already in baseline.** Not a new unplanned addition for this iteration.\n\n### 6. Metadata check in 2-line/3-line joins\n\nLines 733 and 748–750 add `!looksLikeMetadata(mergedLines[i + 1].text)` guards to 2-line joins, and both `mergedLines[i+1]` and `mergedLines[i+2]` checks for 3-line joins:\n\n```typescript\nif (i + 1 < mergedLines.length && !looksLikeMetadata(mergedLines[i + 1].text)) {\n  // 2-line join\n}\nif (i + 2 < mergedLines.length &&\n    !looksLikeMetadata(mergedLines[i + 1].text) &&\n    !looksLikeMetadata(mergedLines[i + 2].text)) {\n  // 3-line join\n}\n```\n\nNot in the iter 30 plan. The motivation is clear: preventing joins like `\"TITLE DLA 4 OSÓB\"` (where a metadata line like a serving count gets merged into a title candidate).\n\nRisk: **Low-medium.** This change is clearly beneficial in intent — joining a title with a serving-count line is never desirable. However it adds filter logic at join time that could prevent a legitimate join if a line is incorrectly classified as metadata. The `looksLikeMetadata` function is already used elsewhere and has its own test coverage, so the classification quality is established. No specific test for this guard path was added.\n\n### 7. Mc/Mac exemption in single-word garbled detection\n\nLine 302:\n\n```typescript\nif (words.length === 1 && /[a-z][A-Z]/.test(text.trim()) && !/^(Mc|Mac)[A-Z]/.test(text.trim())) {\n```\n\nSpecified in iter 29 Change B. The single-word check now exempts `Mc`/`Mac` prefixed names like `\"McDonald\"`. Already in iteration 30 baseline.\n\nRisk: **N/A — already in baseline.**\n\n### 8. New prefix filter for pre-merged continuation singles (lines 1512–1528)\n\nThis is new to this iteration and is a direct consequence of Change 1. Because `buildCandidates` now emits both the standalone and the merged form, both can survive the threshold and appear in `selected`. Without this filter, you'd get two results: `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\"` and `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\"` — the dedup \"shorter wins\" rule would then incorrectly discard the longer complete form.\n\nThe filter at lines 1517–1528 removes a single candidate `s` if there exists another single candidate that starts with `s` + \" \" and has a continuation character immediately after that position:\n\n```typescript\nselected = selected.filter((s) => {\n  if (s.origin !== \"single\") return true;\n  const sLower = s.text.toLowerCase();\n  return !selected.some((other) => {\n    if (other === s || other.origin !== \"single\") return false;\n    const oLower = other.text.toLowerCase();\n    if (!oLower.startsWith(sLower + \" \")) return false;\n    const remainder = oLower.slice(sLower.length + 1);\n    return /^[/&+:(]/.test(remainder);\n  });\n});\n```\n\nThis is a necessary companion to Change 1. Without it, Change 1 would introduce regressions on the `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE` and `Baked Eggs with Feta...` cases that the iter 30 plan's regression watchlist specifically called out. The plan mentioned this risk: \"existing dedup, prefix-removal, and multi-title logic handles this correctly\" — but the existing logic (which operated on 2-line/3-line origins) didn't handle the new same-origin single/single case.\n\nRisk: **Low.** The filter is correctly scoped: it only applies to single-origin candidates, requires the longer form to be a prefix extension with a continuation character at the seam, and is applied after threshold scoring. The condition `/^[/&+:(]/` is identical to the merge condition in `buildCandidates`, ensuring symmetry. The iter 30 plan's regression watchlist cases (`SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS`, `Baked Eggs`) are directly addressed by this filter.\n\nNo explicit unit test for this filter path was added.\n\n---\n\n## C. Plan Correctness: Predicted vs Actual\n\nThe plan predicted 8 of 9 failures would be fixed, with Mushroom Risotto remaining as the unfixable case (title absent from document).\n\nBased on the implementation:\n\n- Pattern A (2 failures from `(` merge): Change 1 should fix both. The standalone is now preserved, `repairOcrText` cleans it, it enters the pool.\n- Pattern B (3 failures same mechanism): Change 1 should fix all three. The plan explicitly lists these as the same root cause.\n- Pattern C (Sole, 1 failure): Change 2 adds `\"sole\"` to dictionary. `repairOcrWord(\"S01e\")` will now find `\"sole\"` and return `\"Sole\"`.\n- Pattern D (Kopytka, 1 failure): Change 3 lowers the Polish threshold to ≥2 words. `\"Ugotuj ziemniaky.\"` (2 words) now triggers the Polish instruction check. `¡→I` repair from iter 29/30 handles the erratic casing on the title.\n- Pattern E (Ogórkowa Zupa, 1 failure): Change 4 raises the pipe+ALL_CAPS cap to 0.22. The plan acknowledges there is uncertainty here — it notes \"the combined positional boost (+0.22 cap) plus any raw embedding signal should clear the threshold\" but doesn't verify the exact raw score for `OGÓRKOWA ZUPA`. If the raw embedding is below `-0.22`, this pattern would still fail. No diagnostic data is provided in the code.\n- Pattern F (Mushroom Risotto, 1 failure): Not addressed. Correctly excluded.\n\n**The plan's prediction is internally consistent with the implementation.** All 4 changes were applied. The 8/9 prediction is likely correct, with the caveat that Pattern E (Change 4) carries the most uncertainty because it depends on an unverified raw embedding score. If `OGÓRKOWA ZUPA` has a raw MiniLM score near or below `-0.22`, it will still fail despite the cap raise.\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\n**A. Plan adherence:** Complete. All 4 changes from the iter 30 plan are implemented exactly as specified, including the specific values (0.22 cap), the exact code structure (continuation merge with `push` before the check), and the dictionary entry (`\"sole\"` not `\"soie\"`).\n\n**B. Unplanned changes:** There are 8 additional changes. The majority (items 1, 2, 3, 5, 7) are carryovers from the iteration 29 plan that were implemented in the iteration 30 codebase (the baseline) rather than being newly added in this commit. The genuinely new unplanned additions in this commit are:\n\n- The `hasErraticCasing` length threshold change (3→5) — low risk, minor reduction in false garbled detections for 3–4 char words\n- The metadata guard in 2-line/3-line joins — low-medium risk, beneficial but lacks targeted test coverage\n- The pre-merged continuation prefix single filter (lines 1512–1528) — necessary companion to Change 1, correctly scoped, no dedicated test\n\nThe pre-merged continuation prefix single filter (item 8) is the most important unplanned addition. It is a required correctness fix for Change 1: without it, the `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS` and `Baked Eggs` regression cases the plan's watchlist warned about would materialize. Its inclusion demonstrates that the implementer worked through the downstream consequences of Change 1 fully. It should have been listed in the plan.\n\n**C. Plan correctness:** The prediction that Changes 1–3 fix 7 of 8 targeted failures is well-grounded. Change 4's effectiveness depends on a specific MiniLM score threshold that was not measured before implementation — this is the one prediction that carries non-trivial uncertainty. The unfixable Mushroom Risotto case is correctly identified and excluded."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a1a08151ad67a0c5d (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 48900\ntool_uses: 14\nduration_ms: 133006</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"cda1f0b1-248e-469a-8a6a-1e44556e08de","uuid":"42df3cb9-b036-49e2-976e-a00fd6107ee2","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Compare the actual code changes in lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts (iteration 30, current HEAD) against the improvement plan at tools/title-loop/docs/30-a2f9b6c/improvement-plan.md.\n\nThe improvement plan specifies 4 changes:\n1. Preserve standalone candidate when continuation-merging (fix 6/9 failures)\n2. Add \"sole\" to food dictionary (fix 1 failure)  \n3. Lower word-count threshold for Polish cooking instruction detection (fix 1 failure)\n4. Raise positional cap to 0.22 for pipe+ALL_CAPS (fix 1 failure)\n\nRead both files and check:\n\nA. **Plan adherence**: Were all 4 planned changes implemented correctly? Any deviations from the plan?\n\nB. **Unplanned changes**: The diff includes several changes NOT in the improvement plan:\n   - `stripTrailingPageRef` function (new)\n   - OCR normalization in `passesHardFilters` (4→a before cooking instruction check)\n   - Multi-word garbled camelCase detection in `isLikelyGarbled`\n   - `hasErraticCasing` threshold change (3→5)\n   - Expanded `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` (4→A, 5→S, ¡→I, €→E, Í/Ì→I)\n   - Metadata check in 2-line/3-line joins\n   - Mc/Mac exemption in garbled detection\n   - New prefix filter for pre-merged continuation singles\n   \n   For each unplanned change: is it clearly beneficial, or does it risk regressions? Does it have test coverage?\n\nC. **Plan correctness**: The plan predicted 8 of 9 failures would be fixed. Does the implementation match this prediction?\n\nRead the files and provide a detailed comparison. Do NOT make code changes.","agentId":"a1a08151ad67a0c5d","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have a full picture. Let me compile the detailed comparison.\n\n---\n\n## Code Review: Iteration 30 Implementation vs Improvement Plan\n\n### Review Metrics\n- Files reviewed: 2 (title-extractor.ts, food-dictionary.ts)\n- Planned changes: 4\n- Planned changes implemented correctly: 4 of 4\n- Unplanned changes found: 8\n- Plan prediction accuracy: matches\n\n---\n\n## A. Plan Adherence — All 4 Planned Changes\n\n**Change 1: Preserve standalone candidate when continuation-merging**\n\nImplemented correctly. The code at lines 654–663 matches the plan's specification exactly:\n\n```typescript\nmergedLines.push(line);  // always keep the original standalone\nif (i + 1 < capsCoalesced.length) {\n  const nextText = capsCoalesced[i + 1].text;\n  if (/^[/&+:(]/.test(nextText)) {\n    mergedLines.push({ text: `${line.text} ${nextText}`, index: line.index });\n    i++;\n    continue;\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThe plan's exact code appears in the file, including the comment `// always keep the original standalone`. One nuance: the plan said the `seen` set downstream handles deduplication; the code confirms this is still the mechanism.\n\n**Change 2: Add \"sole\" to food dictionary**\n\nImplemented correctly. Line 10 of `food-dictionary.ts`:\n\n```\n\"salmon\", \"cod\", \"halibut\", \"tuna\", \"trout\", \"sardine\", \"anchovy\", \"sole\",\n```\n\nThe plan specified adding `\"sole\"` and explicitly warned not to add `\"soie\"`. Both instructions followed.\n\n**Change 3: Lower word-count threshold for Polish cooking instruction detection**\n\nImplemented correctly. The `looksLikeCookingInstruction` function (lines 367–377) matches the plan's pseudocode:\n\n```typescript\nif (POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS.test(text.trim())) {\n  return words.length >= 2;  // Polish: 2+ words is enough\n}\nif (words.length < 4) return false;  // English: keep existing 4-word threshold\nif (COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS.test(text.trim())) return true;\nreturn false;\n```\n\nThe comments are verbatim from the plan. Function structure matches.\n\n**Change 4: Raise positional cap to 0.22 for pipe+ALL_CAPS**\n\nImplemented correctly. Lines 1249–1250:\n\n```typescript\nconst maxPositionalBoost =\n  hasPipePreamble && isAllCaps(firstCandidate.text) ? 0.22 : 0.15;\n```\n\nThe plan specified `0.22` (Option A preferred), used `hasPipePreamble` as the variable name, and the fallback remains `0.15`. Matches exactly.\n\n**Verdict on plan adherence: 4/4, no deviations.**\n\n---\n\n## B. Unplanned Changes — Risk Assessment\n\n### 1. `stripTrailingPageRef` function\n\nThis function was actually specified in the **iteration 29 plan** as Change F, not the iteration 30 plan. The iter 30 plan simply doesn't mention it because it was already documented in iter 29. The function strips trailing `(N)` or `(p. N)` patterns, e.g. `\"Ugotuj ziemniaky. (38)\"` → `\"Ugotuj ziemniaky.\"`. It is applied in `buildCandidates` at line 688 alongside `stripParentheticalGloss` and `stripPageNumber`.\n\nRisk: **Low.** The regex `/\\s*\\((?:p\\.?\\s*)?\\d{1,4}\\)\\s*$/` is tightly scoped to trailing digit-only or `p. N` parentheticals. It cannot strip content-bearing parentheticals like `(variation D)` or `(serves 4)` unless they contain only 1–4 digits with an optional `p.`. The iter 29 plan explicitly validated this function. No test coverage added for it in this iteration.\n\n### 2. OCR normalization in `passesHardFilters` (4→a before cooking instruction check)\n\nAlso specified in iteration 29 plan as Change D. The implementation uses a restricted version — only `4→a` with letter-adjacent context guards:\n\n```typescript\nconst ocrNormForInstruction = text\n  .replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])4/g, \"a\")\n  .replace(/4(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, \"a\");\nif (ocrNormForInstruction !== text && looksLikeCookingInstruction(ocrNormForInstruction)) return false;\n```\n\nThe iter 29 plan suggested also handling `1→i`, `0→o`, `5→s`. The implementation deliberately restricts to only `4→a` with a comment explaining this is the specific artifact causing failures. This is more conservative than the plan suggested, which reduces regression risk.\n\nRisk: **Low.** The `!== text` guard ensures the branch only fires when the substitution actually changed something, preventing any false positive on clean text.\n\n### 3. Multi-word garbled camelCase detection in `isLikelyGarbled`\n\nAlso specified in iteration 29 plan as Change B. The implementation at lines 340–348 adds:\n\n```typescript\nconst hasGarbledCamelCase = words.some(\n  (w) =>\n    w.length >= 3 &&\n    w.length <= 7 &&\n    /[a-z][A-Z]/.test(w) &&\n    !/^(Mc|Mac)[A-Z]/.test(w)\n);\n```\n\nThe iter 29 plan's proposed code lacked the `w.length <= 7` upper bound. The implementation adds it with a comment: \"True garbled tokens like `XxYyZz` or `UuIw` are ≤7 chars.\" This is a deliberate narrowing versus the plan — it prevents false positives from OCR-dropped-space artifacts like `\"withGarlic\"` (10 chars) which would otherwise trigger the check and wrongly reject valid candidates.\n\nRisk: **Low.** The upper bound is a safety addition that only prevents false rejections. Worth noting the bound of 7 is chosen somewhat arbitrarily — a merged word like `\"withSalt\"` (8 chars) would still pass. The reasoning is sound but the specific value could use a unit test.\n\n### 4. `hasErraticCasing` threshold: minimum word length is 5 (not 3)\n\nThe current implementation requires `word.length < 5` to skip:\n\n```typescript\nif (word.length < 5) return false;\n```\n\nThe iter 29 plan doesn't reference this threshold at all; this was introduced in iter 30 itself. Based on the iter 30 commit being the baseline for this plan, the question is whether iter 30's `hasErraticCasing` used length `< 3` previously. The current value is `< 5` — words shorter than 5 characters are not checked for erratic casing. This is more conservative (fewer false detections) than if the threshold were `< 3`.\n\nRisk: **Unclear without prior state.** The comment says \"3→5\" in the task description. If the previous threshold was 3, raising it to 5 means words of 3–4 characters (`\"KoP\"`, `\"aBcD\"`) are now exempt from erratic casing detection. For single-word candidates of length 3–4, this seems safe because they're already filtered by other checks (the `unicodeLetters.length <= 3` garbled check). For multi-word candidates, a 4-character garbled word would no longer be caught by `hasErraticCasing`. This is a small regression risk but likely negligible in practice since 4-character erratic-casing artifacts are rare.\n\n### 5. Expanded `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` (4→A, 5→S, ¡→I, €→E, Í/Ì→I)\n\nSpecified in iteration 29 plan as Change A. The ALL_CAPS branch of `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` now includes:\n\n```typescript\n.replace(/4(?=[A-ZÀ-Ż])/g, \"A\")\n.replace(/(?<=[A-ZÀ-Ż])4/g, \"A\")\n.replace(/5(?=[A-ZÀ-Ż])/g, \"S\")\n.replace(/(?<=[A-ZÀ-Ż])5/g, \"S\")\n.replace(/¡/g, \"I\")\n.replace(/€/g, \"E\")\n.replace(/[ÍÌ]/g, \"I\");\n```\n\nThis was the core of iter 29 Change A. The iter 30 plan did not re-list this because it was already implemented in iteration 30 (iter 30 is the baseline of the iter 30 plan). Confirmed: the iter 30 plan baseline states \"Iteration 30 implemented all 6 changes from the iter 29 plan.\"\n\nRisk: **N/A — already in baseline.** Not a new unplanned addition for this iteration.\n\n### 6. Metadata check in 2-line/3-line joins\n\nLines 733 and 748–750 add `!looksLikeMetadata(mergedLines[i + 1].text)` guards to 2-line joins, and both `mergedLines[i+1]` and `mergedLines[i+2]` checks for 3-line joins:\n\n```typescript\nif (i + 1 < mergedLines.length && !looksLikeMetadata(mergedLines[i + 1].text)) {\n  // 2-line join\n}\nif (i + 2 < mergedLines.length &&\n    !looksLikeMetadata(mergedLines[i + 1].text) &&\n    !looksLikeMetadata(mergedLines[i + 2].text)) {\n  // 3-line join\n}\n```\n\nNot in the iter 30 plan. The motivation is clear: preventing joins like `\"TITLE DLA 4 OSÓB\"` (where a metadata line like a serving count gets merged into a title candidate).\n\nRisk: **Low-medium.** This change is clearly beneficial in intent — joining a title with a serving-count line is never desirable. However it adds filter logic at join time that could prevent a legitimate join if a line is incorrectly classified as metadata. The `looksLikeMetadata` function is already used elsewhere and has its own test coverage, so the classification quality is established. No specific test for this guard path was added.\n\n### 7. Mc/Mac exemption in single-word garbled detection\n\nLine 302:\n\n```typescript\nif (words.length === 1 && /[a-z][A-Z]/.test(text.trim()) && !/^(Mc|Mac)[A-Z]/.test(text.trim())) {\n```\n\nSpecified in iter 29 Change B. The single-word check now exempts `Mc`/`Mac` prefixed names like `\"McDonald\"`. Already in iteration 30 baseline.\n\nRisk: **N/A — already in baseline.**\n\n### 8. New prefix filter for pre-merged continuation singles (lines 1512–1528)\n\nThis is new to this iteration and is a direct consequence of Change 1. Because `buildCandidates` now emits both the standalone and the merged form, both can survive the threshold and appear in `selected`. Without this filter, you'd get two results: `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\"` and `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\"` — the dedup \"shorter wins\" rule would then incorrectly discard the longer complete form.\n\nThe filter at lines 1517–1528 removes a single candidate `s` if there exists another single candidate that starts with `s` + \" \" and has a continuation character immediately after that position:\n\n```typescript\nselected = selected.filter((s) => {\n  if (s.origin !== \"single\") return true;\n  const sLower = s.text.toLowerCase();\n  return !selected.some((other) => {\n    if (other === s || other.origin !== \"single\") return false;\n    const oLower = other.text.toLowerCase();\n    if (!oLower.startsWith(sLower + \" \")) return false;\n    const remainder = oLower.slice(sLower.length + 1);\n    return /^[/&+:(]/.test(remainder);\n  });\n});\n```\n\nThis is a necessary companion to Change 1. Without it, Change 1 would introduce regressions on the `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE` and `Baked Eggs with Feta...` cases that the iter 30 plan's regression watchlist specifically called out. The plan mentioned this risk: \"existing dedup, prefix-removal, and multi-title logic handles this correctly\" — but the existing logic (which operated on 2-line/3-line origins) didn't handle the new same-origin single/single case.\n\nRisk: **Low.** The filter is correctly scoped: it only applies to single-origin candidates, requires the longer form to be a prefix extension with a continuation character at the seam, and is applied after threshold scoring. The condition `/^[/&+:(]/` is identical to the merge condition in `buildCandidates`, ensuring symmetry. The iter 30 plan's regression watchlist cases (`SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS`, `Baked Eggs`) are directly addressed by this filter.\n\nNo explicit unit test for this filter path was added.\n\n---\n\n## C. Plan Correctness: Predicted vs Actual\n\nThe plan predicted 8 of 9 failures would be fixed, with Mushroom Risotto remaining as the unfixable case (title absent from document).\n\nBased on