{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_014jTKoSoZTXQBkdTUJiVAG4","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see the full eval results. Let me count failures:\n\nFailures (marked \"no\"):\n1. Line 26: `Braised Cod with White Wine` → empty (still failing)\n2. Line 40: `Drożdże Sernik` → `Podawać letni lub chłodny.` (still failing)\n3. Line 54: `Kopytka z Pieczarkami Leśnymi` → `Ugotuj ziemniaky.` (still failing - Change 3 didn't work?)\n4. Line 65: `Mushroom Risotto` → wrong (expected - not fixable)\n\n\n5. Line 68: `Ogórkowa Zupa` → empty (still failing - Change 4 didn't work?)\n6. Line 78: `Piernik z Śliwkami` → `Podawać ciepło ze śmietaną lub lodami.` (still failing)\n7. Line 86: `Roasted Beet and Walnut Dip` → empty (still failing)\n8. Line 97: `Sole with Brown Butter and Capers` → `Soie with Brown Butter and Capers` (still failing - Change 2 didn't work?)\n9. Line 108 appears to be cut off, so I need to see what comes next to understand the full picture.\n\nLooking at the results file from the baseline commit, I'm seeing 9 failures across various recipe entries. The key insight here is that these results are from the baseline evaluation, not from my current uncommitted changes. The working directory has modifications to the title extractor and food dictionary that should fix these issues, but the test results I'm looking at are from before those changes were applied. The unit tests pass with my current code, so the improvements should be working in the actual implementation.\n\nNow I'm noticing something odd with the \"Baked Eggs\" case — the results file shows it passing, but when I ran the CLI directly, it's missing the \"& Coriander\" suffix. This suggests either the results file is from a different version of the code, or there's a discrepancy between what the test harness is evaluating and what the actual extraction pipeline is producing. I need to verify whether the model is being reloaded fresh with each invocation or if there's caching happening. The real issue here is that \"Baked Eggs\" is dropping the `& Coriander` suffix, which matches the regression the plan predicted. Let me examine whether the new prefix filter is actually removing the merged form when it should be keeping it.\n\nThe filter logic removes the shorter variant if a longer one exists that starts with it followed by the pattern `/&+:(`. So if both \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\" and the version with `& Coriander` survive the filter, the longer one should remain. But I need to check if the merged form is even passing through the filter in the first place.\n\nLooking at the hard filter at line 455, it requires at least 8 words and no special characters unless they're in the exception pattern. The merged version has 9 words and contains ` & `, which is in the exception, so it should pass. But here's the issue: the old code only kept the merged form in `mergedLines`, while the new code keeps both the standalone and merged form. Now both are entering the pipeline as single-origin candidates and going through the same filtering steps.\n\nThe problem is that if the merged form scores lower than the standalone (maybe due to its extra length or a slightly different embedding from MiniLM), it could get filtered out while the standalone survives — which would be the regression. The merged form is longer at 9 words versus 7, and even though the hard filter allows it, the scoring might not favor it. I should run the full evaluation rather than getting stuck on individual cases—that'll show me exactly where regressions happened. Looking at the real file results, I'm seeing some concerning patterns like the `Baked Eggs` case missing the `& Coriander` suffix, which suggests the logic might not be working as expected. Looking at the comparison between iteration 30 and my current run, I'm seeing clear regressions — the green beans entry is getting extra translations appended when it shouldn't, and the baked eggs output is missing the coriander component that was there before. These changes must have introduced bugs that are degrading the output quality.\n\nLet me trace through what's happening with the continuation merge logic, since that's likely where the standalone forms are leaking through when they should be filtered out. I should run the full evaluation to get a complete picture of what's broken across all test cases.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3172,"cache_read_input_tokens":85666,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3172},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"cda1f0b1-248e-469a-8a6a-1e44556e08de","uuid":"980b2f58-c62d-4079-a250-0c2e4ba66eb0"}
