{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_013idNt5WwypxVFzmLTXK6fX","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the issues:\n\n**Baked Eggs regression**: The input has:\n- Line 1: `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce`\n- Line 2: `& Coriander`\n\nWith the old code, line 2 (`& Coriander`) starts with `&`, so the continuation merge would merge it with line 1, producing `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander` as the ONLY candidate (the standalone was lost).\n\nWith the new code (Change 1), both the standalone `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce` and the merged `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander` enter the pool. \n\nThe prefix filter should eliminate the standalone, but the CLI is showing it winning instead—which means either the merged form isn't meeting the threshold, the prefix filter has a bug, or the dedup logic that favors shorter strings is running first and removing the merged candidate before the prefix filter gets a chance.\n\nLet me trace through the execution order: structural heading removal, join protection, then the prefix filter at 1517-1528 that should catch this case, followed by sub-section header removal, multi-line join protection, position-0 compound protection, and finally dedup. So the prefix filter runs before dedup, which means if both forms make it to `selected`, the standalone should get filtered out and the merged form should survive.\n\nThe issue might be that the merged form `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander` fails the word count threshold—it's 9 words, so it should pass the `>= 8` requirement, but I need to check if the ampersand with spaces around it is being handled correctly by the word-splitting logic. The extracted title is missing the final part with the ampersand and coriander, so it fails the match check. Looking at the results, iteration 30 had the correct full title, which means something