ters but scores lower, so the old behavior of only emitting the merged form would have prevented this regression.\n\nThe real fix is simpler: after thresholding, if a standalone exists but its merged counterpart didn't make the cut despite passing hard filters, I should still prefer the merged form since it's the more complete candidate.\n\nActually, let me reconsider—the targeted approach is to only emit the standalone when the merged form fails the hard filters, not the threshold. I'm writing the logic to check if the next line starts with a continuation character like `/`, `&`, `+`, or `(`, and if so, create the merged version and add it to the candidates.\n\nRefining the merge logic...\n\nBut wait, calling `passesHardFilters` here creates a problem since the text hasn't gone through the full processing pipeline yet, so the results might differ from later stages. A simpler fix would be to always emit both versions and let the downstream deduplication handle it.\n\nActually, the real issue is clearer now: the prefix filter removes standalones when merged forms survive the threshold, but if the merged form fails the threshold, the standalone incorrectly wins. What I need is to prefer the merged form whenever it exists in the scored candidates, even if it didn't pass the threshold—that way the deduplication logic can properly suppress the standalone.\n\nLet me reconsider the approach by checking what the `seen` set actually deduplicates on. The CLI test shows the regression is real — the merged form is getting truncated to just `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce` without the `& Coriander` part. So the question is whether the merged text actually fails the hard filters, which I can't determine without running the model. The fix I'm leaning toward is Option A: only emit the standalone when the merged form fails hard filters, since we're already checking hard filters downstream anyway in the processing loop.\n\nBut looking at Option B more carefully — instead of checking against the selected candidates in the prefix filter, I could check against the scored candidates (everything that passed hard filters and got scored, regardless of threshold). If the merged form exists in scored and passed hard filters, I'd remove the standalone from the final selection. This approach is safer because it means we'd prefer the merged form over an incomplete standalone version, even if the merged form didn't hit the scoring threshold.\n\nThe code structure supports this: `scored` is defined earlier in the function, and the prefix filter runs later on `selected`. I could modify that filter to reference `scored` instead.\n\nModifying the filter logic...\n\nThe key insight is that I need to check against the full `scored` array instead of just `selected`, so that even candidates that fell below the threshold can still disqualify shorter forms if a more complete merged version exists. This handles the case where a longer, more descriptive title scored lower but is still the better choice.\n\nActually, wait—this approach would eliminate the standalone even if the merged form had a poor score, which could be wrong. Let me reconsider: the merged form like \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" is the actual complete title, and the standalone \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\" is just an incomplete fragment. I should always prefer the complete version if it passes hard filters. The standalone should only be generated in the first place if the merged form fails hard filters—like when it's too long or corrupted. So the real fix belongs at candidate generation time: only emit the standalone when the merged form doesn't make it through hard filters.\n\nLooking at the actual code flow, both the merged and standalone entries go through the same `passesHardFilters` check independently, and both are making it into candidates. The problem is downstream where the scoring logic prefers the standalone. Option A—filtering at generation time—is the cleanest solution.\n\nI'm modifying the merge logic to only emit the standalone form as a fallback when the merged version fails the hard filters, using OCR repair to determine if the merged text is valid. I'm tracing through how `stripParentheticalGloss` handles the OCR corruption case — it extracts \"Braised Cod with White Wine\" as the base and \"OCR CORRUPTION: digit for letter, hyphenation\" as the parenthetical, but since the parenthetical isn't all caps, it returns the full text unchanged, so the merged form still fails the hard filter and gets emitted as expected. The colon in \"CORRUPTION:\" doesn't have spaces around it, so the regex check passes. But there's also a filter at line 444 that rejects text starting with \"(OCR\", which doesn't apply here since the merged form starts with \"Braised\". Let me trace through what happens with the actual text content. the regex doesn't match, so the word count check fails and the merged form gets filtered out, leaving just the standalone version. Now I'm realizing that with my proposed fix, I'd need to run the merged text through the same repair pipeline as the single text computation to ensure consistent processing.\n\nActually, there's a cleaner approach: I can apply the OCR repair and stripping functions to the merged text, then check if it passes the hard filters. If it does, I use the merged version; if not, I fall back to the standalone. This way the merged text goes through the exact same validation pipeline as individual candidates, ensuring consistency across both cases. Sauce & Coriander\". After processing: same text (no OCR artifacts). `passesHardFilters`: 9 words with `&` → passes (exception for `& `). So `!passesHardFilters` is false, standalone NOT emitted. ✓\n\n2. `(OCR CORRUPTION...)` case: merged = \"Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne (OCR CORRUPTION: digit for letter, hyphenation)\". After `repairOcrText`: \"Braised Cod with White Wine (OCR CORRUPTION: digit for letter, hyphenation)\". `passesHardFilters`: 11 words without valid separator → fails. So `!passesHardFilters` is true, standalone IS emitted. ✓\n\nThis fix works! Let me implement it.\n\nNow I'm checking the Smażona zielona fasolka case. Line 2 doesn't match the continuation pattern, so the old behavior was correct with just the first line. But the current run is merging all three lines together, which suggests this regression is coming from somewhere else in the logic. The bilingual detection logic checks whether the 2-line join candidate looks like a translation pair by examining the first word of each line — if the first word at position 0 is mixed-case Polish and the second is ALL_CAPS English, it should suppress this as a valid bilingual match. Let me trace through the detection logic to see where this is failing. The filter checks if the scored candidate's text (lowercased) starts with, ends with a space before, or contains a space before the translation candidate — and if any of these match, it's excluded. For the 2-line join, the text ends with \" green beans borkeum\", so it gets filtered out of the threshold calculation. However, it's still present in the selected results, which is the issue.\n\nActually, wait — I need to reconsider. The `selected` array is filtered from `scoredForThreshold`, not from the full `scored` array. Since the 2-line join is excluded from `scoredForThreshold` entirely, it shouldn't appear in `selected` at all. So if `selected` only contains \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" from position 0, then the join is being correctly excluded.\n\nBut the current output is showing both \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" and \"GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\", which shouldn't happen. Something's changed, maybe in how the continuation merge is working. Let me trace through the mergedLines more carefully — particularly how the ALL_CAPS coalescing logic is handling \"GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\" as a potential heading candidate. None of these lines start with the continuation characters, so the merge change doesn't apply here. Now I'm checking whether the `hasErraticCasing` threshold could be the culprit — looking at `Smażona zielona fasolka`, the word `Smażona` has an uppercase `Ż` in the middle, which might trigger the erratic casing detection...\n\nChecking the logic...\n\nI'm verifying whether `ż` (lowercase, U+017C) falls within the range `à-ż` (U+00E0 to U+017C), and it does since it's at the boundary, so the regex should correctly identify it as a lowercase character in the inner portion of the word.\n\nFor Korean text like `그린빈`, the letter-extraction logic strips out non-ASCII characters, leaving an empty string, which triggers the garbled text detection since there aren't enough letters to analyze.\n\nI'm trying to figure out what's causing the Smażona regression. It could be a flaky result from model loading differences across separate CLI invocations, or there might be floating-point variance. Let me re-run the problematic cases to verify whether this is actually a regression or just noise from a single run. The Baked Eggs case is definitely a real issue I need to fix, but I should confirm the Smażona behavior before deciding if it needs attention too.\n\nLooking more carefully at the results, I see that the extracted text for Smażona now includes extra content like \"GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\" appended to it. The match function normalizes both strings to uppercase and checks if all parts of the expected text are contained in the extracted text. Let me trace through what's happening with the normalization and matching logic to understand why this is still returning a match. Looking at the results.txt format more carefully — it shows `expected | extracted - yes/no`, so in iteration 30 the extracted value was exactly `Smażona zielona fasolka`, but now it's coming back with the extra text `GREEN BEANS BORKEUM` appended. The eval still passes because the substring match succeeds, but this is a behavioral change. I need to figure out whether this regression came from the uncommitted changes or was already present.\n\nSince the results.txt was generated from the committed code, and I've already ruled out the continuation merge change and other modifications as relevant here, let me just run this specific file again to check if the output is deterministic, then move forward with fixing the Baked Eggs regression and running the full test suite.\n\nThe fix is simpler than modifying candidate generation—I'll update the prefix filter to check against all scored candidates rather than just the threshold-surviving ones, so the standalone form gets filtered out even when the merged continuation didn't make the threshold cutoff.\n\nRefining the filter logic... I see the issue now — I should only emit the standalone when the merged form actually fails the hard filters, not just because it scores poorly. That way, if the merged form passes validation, it becomes the correct title, but if it gets rejected for being too long or violating other constraints, the standalone serves as a fallback. Let me refactor the continuation merge logic to process the merged text through the same pipeline as single-line candidates.\n\nBuilding the merge pipeline... I'm realizing the current approach emits either the merged form or the standalone as a fallback, but the improvement plan calls for always emitting both. The plan has shown regressions though, so I need to reconsider. The real issue is that scoring and thresholding pick the standalone even when the merged form is valid. I'm thinking the cleanest solution is to emit both forms always, but add a rawScore guard—only suppress the standalone if the merged form scores above a certain threshold like -0.2, otherwise keep both.\n\nActually, the simplest fix is just to emit the standalone as a fallback only when the merged form fails hard filters. This is a minimal two-line change that reverts to conditional emission. For annotation merges, the merged form fails and the standalone survives; for