ld complicate things too much. Let me step back—the real issue is that the merged form might get filtered out by the threshold even though it should be kept. So instead of changing how candidates are generated or scored, I'll modify the prefix filter to check against the full scored list rather than just selected, and make sure to pull the merged form into selected if it exists in scored but hasn't been added yet.\n\nWriting the filter logic... Refactoring the filter logic...\n\nI'm using a separate accumulator array to collect merged items, then filtering the original selection to remove singles that have a matching continuation, and finally pushing the accumulated merged items back. This avoids the issue of modifying the array while iterating over it. But I'm realizing there might be an even simpler approach—maybe I should just prevent emitting the standalone form in the first place when a merged version exists.\n\nLooking at the actual consequences: with Option A, the Baked Eggs case would revert to its original behavior where only the merged form gets emitted, which wasn't a regression. For OCR annotations, the merged form would fail the hard filters and fall back to the standalone, which would fix those failures. Smażona wouldn't be affected since it has no continuation merge. So Option A essentially restores the old behavior while still fixing the specific issue.\n\nThe prefix filter at 1517-1528 would become dead code since both forms can't be in `selected` anymore, but I can leave it as a safety net without harm. I'm going to implement Option A by modifying the candidate generation logic to only emit the standalone form as a fallback when the merge fails hard filters.\n\nImplementing the fix... Still writing merge logic...\n\nThe plan expected both standalone and merged forms to be generated, but empirically that causes a regression. My fix changes this to only emit the merged form when it passes validation, falling back to standalone otherwise. Let me trace